issue.title: Feature ui
issue.body: too many features to count, mainly relating to UI functionality

issue.title: Feature draw board
issue.body: Draws the board and its tiles to the screen

issue.title: Connect board continuation
issue.body: This branch has the code that maps out the board in a proper fashion.

issue.title: Resource production
issue.body:
Completed features:
- Resources distributed based on where settlements are placed
- Resources are limited (19 of each resource)
- Corners are now represented by circles on the screen. Can be clicked to change settlement intersection.
- Adjacency rule has been applied for above feature.

NOTE: Corners for the perimeter of the board still needs to be developed. This will be implemented once a consensus is reached on whether ports and water should be represented with tiles or not.

issue.title: Third ring of tiles
issue.body:
- The screen now has a third ring of tiles representing water tiles and ports.
- The settlements for the island perimeter are now implemented.

issue.title: Building phase
issue.body:
- Separate phase for building is now implemented (cannot build roads or development cards in the meantime though)
- Board starts off with preset settlements so that the user can test functionality for resource collection and building in a proper fashion.

issue.title: Refactoring session 1
issue.body:
- Code was refactored to respect PEP8 formatting
- Bank classes were added to put the resources and game pieces into each of their own classes.

issue.title: UI Rework
issue.body:
The UI has been revamped to have the following changes:
- Window dimensions were modified so that the width is greater than the height, alongside being smaller in general.
- Public player information now exists and is present on the left side of the screen.
- Buttons and Private player information is now displayed on the right side of the screen.
- Notification Panels are now used to indicate current phase of the player's turn and to give feedback when an improper action is done.
- Icons representing resources, game pieces, and development cards (in preparation for its implementation) are now shown in the screen in place of direct text.

issue.title: Randomization optimization
issue.body: Implemented an optimization so that tile tokens with 6 and 8 are never adjacent to each other. This is to make the game more balanced.

issue.title: Victory points for settlements & cities, Winning games, and starting new games.
issue.body:
- Victory points are now earned based on the player's amount of settlements and cities placed.
- Once a player reaches 10 points during their turn, ending the turn ends the game and announces the winner (If points are earned outside the turn, the player must wait for their turn before ending their turn to win).
- A new game can be initiated after the winning results are announced.

issue.title: Setup phase settlements
issue.body:
Has the following implementations:
- Random turn order established.
- Placement of settlements during setup phase implemented
- Reverse turn order for placement of second settlement.
- Resource collection upon placement of second settlement.

issue.title: Refactoring session 2
issue.body:
Some architectural changes have been made:
- Minor refactoring done to back-end classes (coding conventions for the most part).
- Die Roller is no longer relegated to a button but is rather involved with the board facade to reduce coupling (so that a button does not have direct access to back-end logic).
- Button class was deleted and replaced with a Submit button that has similar functionality (this is to give it distinct purpose. In the future, another button type for the sole purpose of incrementing/decrementing inventory content will exist).
- InventoryPanel was created in order to allow the player's inventory to be displayed in a cleaner fashion.

issue.title: Inventory buttons
issue.body: Inventory buttons are now present near the player's resources. These buttons are setup for future features to come.

issue.title: Refactoring Ceten Design
issue.body:
- This refactoring session involved a significant overhaul of Ceten's program design. This involved improving the separation of concern for classes (e.g. Ceten is solely responsible for control handling, Facades are solely responsible for handling UI components and invoking back-end code that the facade is tied to).
- Classes with common behavior was abstracted.
- Some code quality was improved along the way.
- All debugging information that was printed to the console is now deleted.
- Irrelevant files present in the codebase was deleted.
- The robber now cannot be placed on the same tile he is currently in.

issue.title: Refactoring board connections
issue.body:
This implementation completely refactors the design of the core mechanics of Ceten, since Tiles, Edges, and Corners are the essence of a Ceten game.
- Tiles, Edges, and Corners are now completely refactored to have a much more optimal design.
- Tiles now have an abstract coordinate system so that Edges and Corners have a much more reliable basis of properly connecting with the Tiles during the map building process.
- Tiles now have access to both Edges and Corners, eliminating the Edge's role as the middleman between Tiles and Corners and ultimately making communication between the three components more efficient.
- Implementation for Tile and Corner facades have been made simpler due to the above changes.
- Some additional refactoring has been done to improve code quality due to the significant code changes warranting some refactoring in areas that play a key role with Tiles, Edges, and Corners.
- Unused files and code have now been removed.

issue.title: Road Building
issue.body:
Roads have now been implemented. A fair amount of mechanics in this game were changed to adapt to the introduction of roads:
- For the setup phase, one road can be placed per turn. The road must be placed adjacent to the settlement placed in that same turn.
- Settlements can now only be placed adjacent to roads during the game phase.
- Roads can only be placed adjacent to the player's other roads during the game phase. This cannot be done if a different player's settlement stands in the way between the player's road and where the player wants to place the road.

issue.title: Maritime Trade
issue.body:
- All buttons are now disabled during phases in which they have no use.
- UI components for Maritime Trade have been utilized and enable and disable properly depending on the current context
- Players can now trade resources with the game for other, more desired resources
- Placing settlements near ports improve the trade rates (3:1 for standard, 2:1 for a specialized port using the corresponding resource of said port to trade with).

issue.title: Victory points for largest army.

labels.name: story
labels.description: Top-level description for an important game component that needs to be implemented.

issue.body: Those with the most knight cards played shall be given the Largest Army card (which offers 2 victory points). This card is first offered to the one who played 3 knight cards. The card is subsequently then given to the one who plays more knight cards than the one who currently has the Largest Army card.

issue.title: Victory points for longest road

labels.name: story
labels.description: Top-level description for an important game component that needs to be implemented.

issue.body: Award the "Largest Road" card (provides two victory points) for those who has the longest road. Note that this card is only rewarded for the first one to get a road of length 5. After that point, the one who builds a longer road gets that card for themselves. Also note that settlements can be used to split a road apart, potentially reducing the longest road for the player subject to that split.

- Trading resources to get one.
- Moving the robber upon use of a knight card.
- Largest Army card given depending on Knight cards played.
- Developing the actions of various progress cards.
- Additional victory points for victory cards.

milestone.title: Release 2.0
milestone.description:
Ceten Lite: This version of Ceten will represent the core components of the game of Catan.
It includes the following game mechanics: Collecting Resources, Placing the Robber to halt resource production, Maritime Trading, and Building Settlements and Roads. The following game mechanics are omitted: Robber forcing players to discard 8+ resources, Player who invoked the robber stealing a resource at random from a player of choice with a settlement adjacent to the robber, Additional 2 victory points for longest road, and Development Cards

To account for the fact that only the core game components are present, the first to reach 6 victory points wins Ceten (rather than the usual 10).

The full version of Ceten will potentially be released in Release 3.0.

issue.body:
Maritime trade involves trading a particular amount of one resource for one of another resource. The following exchange rates are used (given:received):

4:1 - No ports claimed
3:1 - Standard port claimed
2:1 - Specialized port claimed. This exchange rate is only applied if the specialized port specializes in the same resource that the player is giving.
